speeches.content:
President, an event was held in Hong Kong on 2 October and the name of the event was "High-level Roundtable on Gender Identity, Rights and the Law".  It was organized by a number of organizations, including the Centre for Comparative and Public Law of the University of Hong Kong and the United Nations Development Programme, among others.  It was attended by a large number of people, particularly people from the medical and legal professions, transgender persons, activists, non-governmental organization workers, academics, educators, and so on.  At the end of the conference, they actually came up with a number of key messages which, I believe, would give this Council a global perspective on how we look at the issue of gender recognition.  So, I want to read them out and have it entered into the record of our Council.  The key messages are: 
(1) Gender recognition, in documents and in law, is important for transgender people;   
(2) Without such recognition, it is difficult or impossible to enjoy the rights and opportunities available to other people in one's society;  
(3) Failure to extend recognition is a rights issue and has consequences for transgender people's health and well being;  
(4) Onerous preconditions for recognition, like depriving many transgender persons of opportunities to be recognized in their experienced gender, run counter to international rights norms and state commitments under key international conventions.  They also make no sense on health grounds;  
(5) Medical preconditions involving surgery (including sterilization surgery) and hormones are particularly problematic, on the grounds that they serve to coerce people into undergoing medical procedures. Some of those procedures are invasive, complex and often beset with complications.  They may be medically inadvisable for some transgender people; 
(6) We endorse recent calls by influential voices in health and rights (including the WHO, UNDP, OHCHR, UN Women, UNAIDS, UNFPA, UNICEF, the UN Special Rapporteur on Torture, OSF, WPATH, Amnesty International and the American Medical Association) for more progressive policies on gender recognition for transgender persons;  
(7) We endorse the Global Commission on HIV and the Law's recommendations related to transgender people and calling on countries to: 
(i) stop punishing transgender people for being who they are. Instead, repeal laws that criminalize behaviour associated with transgender identity and amend anti-discrimination laws to explicitly include gender identity, non-conforming gender status and sexual orientation;  
(ii) ensure that transgender people have access to health care supplies and services (including preventive services) in 
non-discriminatory environments as well as access to healthcare personnel trained to respond to their unique medical and health needs;  
(iii) remove existing barriers (whether legal, administrative or regulatory) that prohibit transgender and people of non-conforming gender status from forming public community organizations and associations;  
(iv) recognize and respect existing civil and religious laws and practices that support individual privacy; and  
(v) change laws and administrative policies to enable transgender people to obtain identification documents that reflect their lived gender, whether or not they have undergone any gender-related medical procedures.   
(8) We agree with the recent Open Society Foundations Report (OSF Report), which is called "License to be Yourself", on gender recognition listing the following best practices in regard to gender recognition:  
(i) recognition based on self-defined gender identity, with no pathologizing diagnosis required;  
(ii) recognition that does not require forced sterilization or medical procedures;  
(iii) recognition that does not require living continuously or permanently in one's gender identity;  
(iv) recognition that does not require divorce or a civil partnership; 
(v) recognition that allows existing or prospective parenting;  
(vi) recognition that is available to children;  
(vii) recognition that includes intersex people;  
(viii) recognition that applies to all residents, including those born overseas; and  
(ix) procedures that are simple, timely, low-cost, transparent rather that discretionary and protective of privacy.   
(9) We note that an increasing number of jurisdictions worldwide are adopting more progressive policies along the lines of what is recommended by the Global Commission on HIV and the Law and in the OSF Report.  We welcome court decisions from South Asia, including Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Pakistan, recognizing third gender identity without medical preconditions.  We also welcome gender identity legislation from Argentina and Denmark, in which individuals are able to determine their legal gender status through a simple administrative process; and  
(10) We urge Hong Kong legislators ― those of us sitting here or not in the Chamber ― to reject any legislative proposals that require of transgender people that they undergo any form of medical treatment as a precondition for gender recognition.   
So, President, the Professional Commons and I will be voting against and voting "nay" to the Marriage (Amendment) Bill 2014 because we believe that it is exactly what this Bill is trying to do, which is to force transgender people to undergo unnecessary or torturous medical treatment as a precondition for gender recognition.  We support the advocacy for the Hong Kong Government to seriously look into the establishment of a gender recognition act.   
Thank you, President.
